other_text: ['There are 4 species recorded in Tanzania: Mops brachyptera, Mops condylurus, Mops niveiventer and Mops thersites.  The ears are joined at the base, but the only way to positively identify this genus is to examine the last tooth in the upper toothrow, which is reduced.']
['There are 3 species recorded from Tanzania: Tadarida aegyptiaca, Tadarida fulminans and Tadarida ventralis.  Look for the large emargination at the front of the palate to distinguish this bat.']

['There are 6 species recorded from Tanzania: Chaerephon ansorgei, Chaerephon bemmeleni, Chaerephon bivittata, Chaerephon major, Chaerephon nigeriae and Chaerephon pumila.  These bats have wrinkled lips and ears that join together on the top of the rostrum.  Look for a band of light colored fur under the wing where it joins the body.']

other_text: ['There are 2 species known from Tanzania: Glauconycteris argentata and Glauconycteris variegata.  The butterfly bats are characterized by the very short snout and hooked tragi.  Look for a golden stripe where the wing inserts on the body of Glauconycteris argentata and a reticulated pattern on the wing and tail membranes of Glauconycteris variegata.']

['There are 4 species known in Tanzania: Neoromicia capensis, Neoromicia melckorum, Neoromicia rendalli and Neoromicia tenuipinnis.  These insectivorous bats are brown with black wings, short ears and stubby tragi.  They have only one upper incisor.  ']

other_text: ['There are 4 species recorded in Tanzania: Mops brachyptera, Mops condylurus, Mops niveiventer and Mops thersites.  The ears are joined at the base, but the only way to positively identify this genus is to examine the last tooth in the upper toothrow, which is reduced.']
['There are 3 species recorded from Tanzania: Tadarida aegyptiaca, Tadarida fulminans and Tadarida ventralis.  Look for the large emargination at the front of the palate to distinguish this bat.']

['There are 6 species recorded from Tanzania: Chaerephon ansorgei, Chaerephon bemmeleni, Chaerephon bivittata, Chaerephon major, Chaerephon nigeriae and Chaerephon pumila.  These bats have wrinkled lips and ears that join together on the top of the rostrum.  Look for a band of light colored fur under the wing where it joins the body.']
